  = Novel Oral Solid Dosage Forms Based on Solid Dispersion Technology
])

#align(center, text(11pt)[
  A Review of Dripping Pills, Orally Disintegrating Tablets, and Orodispersible
  Films
])

#v(1em)

= 1 Abstract

Solid dispersion (SD) technology has been widely applied in the development of
novel oral solid dosage forms to improve the solubility, dissolution rate, and
bioavailability of poorly water-soluble drugs, as well as to achieve modified
release profiles. This report reviews three categories of novel oral solid
dosage forms: (1) dripping pills (solid dispersion-based), covering both
dissolution enhancement and sustained release applications; (2) orally
disintegrating tablets (ODTs), focusing on formulation strategies, manufacturing
technologies, and disintegration performance; and (3) orodispersible films
(ODFs), examining formulation components, preparation methods, and
disintegration characteristics. For each category, representative published
papers are summarized with details on drug, matrix/excipients, method, and key
results.

= 2 Dripping Pills Based on Solid Dispersion

== 2.1 Principles of Solid Dispersion in Dripping Pills

Solid dispersion (SD) refers to the dispersion of one or more active ingredients
in an inert carrier or matrix in the solid state, typically achieved by melting,
solvent, or melting-solvent methods. When applied to dripping pills, the drug is
dispersed in a molten carrier (hydrophilic or hydrophobic), dripped into an
immiscible cooling medium, and solidified into spherical pills. This process
converts the drug into an amorphous or molecularly dispersed state, thereby
enhancing its solubility, dissolution rate, and bioavailability. Hydrophilic
carriers such as polyethylene glycol (PEG) 4000 to 6000, poloxamer, and gelatin
are commonly used for immediate release, while hydrophobic carriers such as
stearic acid and hydrogenated vegetable oil can be employed for sustained
release (Zuo et al., 2021).

== 2.2 Dissolution Improvement: Lycopene Dripping Pills

This section summarizes the work of Chang et al. (2016).

*Drug*: Lycopene, a natural carotenoid with potent antioxidant, anti-cancer, and
anti-hyperlipidemic activities. It is practically water-insoluble, resulting in
extremely low oral bioavailability.

*Matrix*: PEG 6000 as the primary hydrophilic carrier, with Cremophor EL and
Tween 80 as emulsifiers to optimize solubility and dissolution.

*Method*: The dripping pills were prepared by the hot melt method (solid
dispersion technique). PEG 6000 was melted at 70 degree C, and tomato extract
(containing lycopene), Cremophor EL, and Tween 80 were added and mixed
thoroughly. The molten mixture was gravitationally extruded through a dripping
machine and dropped into a cooling bath (liquid paraffin at 0 to 5 degree C) to
form spherical pills. A 3^2 full factorial design was employed to optimize the
formulation with Cremophor EL (factor A) and Tween 80 (factor B) as independent
variables, and solubility, dissolution at pH 1.2 and pH 6.8, and 6-month
stability as responses.

*Results*: The optimal formulation (F8: 10 g Cremophor EL, 15 g Tween 80)
exhibited significantly enhanced solubility and dissolution compared to raw
lycopene. DSC and PXRD analysis confirmed that lycopene was converted to the
amorphous state within the PEG 6000 matrix, with no recrystallization detected.
In vitro dissolution studies showed rapid release in both pH 1.2 and pH 6.8
media. In vivo pharmacokinetic studies in rats demonstrated an approximately
6-fold improvement in oral bioavailability compared to free lycopene, confirming
the effectiveness of the dripping pill solid dispersion approach.

== 2.3 Sustained Release: TCM Pills and Dripping Pill Drug Release

This section draws on the comprehensive review by Zuo et al. (2021).

*Background*: Traditional Chinese Medicine (TCM) pills represent one of the
oldest solid dosage forms, with historical records dating back to 206 to 220 BC.
Among the various pill types (honeyed pill, watered pill, pasted pill, waxed
pill, concentrated pill, and dripping pill), the dripping pill introduced in the
1980s is manufactured through a solid dispersion method and represents a
modernization of TCM pill technology.

*Matrix/Carriers*: Dripping pill bases are classified into two categories: (1)
Hydrophilic bases: PEG, poloxamer, and gelatin providing fast dissolution for
immediate-release formulations; (2) Hydrophobic bases: Stearic acid,
hydrogenated vegetable oil, and beeswax that retard water penetration and drug
diffusion, enabling sustained or modified release.

*Method*: The dripping pill preparation process involves: (a) melting herbal
extracts and the selected base together; (b) dripping the molten mixture into an
immiscible, non-interacting cooling medium (typically liquid paraffin or
silicone oil); (c) congealing the droplets into solid pills.

*Release Profiles*: Zuo et al. (2021) provide a systematic classification of TCM
pill release patterns. According to the USP classification, different pill types
correspond to different drug release profiles:

- Immediate release: Watered pills, dripping pills (with hydrophilic bases),
  honeyed pills, water-honeyed pills, and concentrated pills, where no effort is
  made to modify drug release.
- Extended release: Pasted pills (for sustained dissolving) and waxed pills (for
  difficult dissolving), which are designed to prolong drug release over time.
  Historical TCM texts describe: "use pasted pills for their sustained
  dissolving, use waxed pill for their difficult dissolving."
- Delayed release: Some coated pill variants provide delayed release.

*Key Findings*: The review found that dissolution rates of TCM pills were
generally slower than their modern counterparts (tablets and capsules). In a
comparative study of Fuzi Lizhong Pills, index components were continuously
released over 24 hours, supporting the sustained-release design of traditional
pill formulations. The use of hydrophobic carriers in dripping pills (stearic
acid, hydrogenated oils) allows formulators to achieve controlled drug release
profiles, bridging ancient pharmaceutical wisdom with modern modified-release
technology.

= 3 Orally Disintegrating Tablets (ODTs)

This section summarizes the comprehensive review by Fu et al. (2004).

== 3.1 Background

Orally fast disintegrating tablets (FDTs), also known as orally disintegrating
tablets (ODTs) or orodispersible tablets, are solid dosage forms that
disintegrate or dissolve rapidly in the oral cavity without additional water.
Dysphagia (difficulty in swallowing) affects approximately 35% of the general
population and 30 to 40% of elderly institutionalized patients, driving the
demand for ODTs. The European Pharmacopoeia defines orodispersible tablets as
those that disintegrate in less than 3 minutes in the mouth before swallowing.

== 3.2 Formulation Analysis

ODT formulations typically include the following key excipients:

- Superdisintegrants: Crospovidone, croscarmellose sodium, sodium starch
  glycolate rapidly swell upon contact with water, promoting tablet breakup.
- Saccharides: Mannitol, sorbitol, lactose provide sweetness, mouthfeel, and act
  as fillers. Mannitol is preferred due to its negative heat of solution
  (cooling sensation).
- Effervescent agents: Sodium bicarbonate plus citric acid generate CO2 to
  accelerate disintegration.
- Binders: Low levels of PVP, HPMC, or gelatin to maintain tablet strength
  without compromising disintegration.
- Taste-masking agents: Coatings, sweeteners, or flavorings to mask bitter
  drugs, as the tablet dissolves in close proximity to taste buds.

== 3.3 Manufacturing Procedures

Fu et al. (2004) review multiple manufacturing technologies:

1. Lyophilization (Freeze-Drying): The drug solution or suspension is frozen and
  then dried under vacuum, producing a highly porous, lightweight tablet (e.g.,
  Zydis technology). This provides the fastest disintegration (a few seconds)
  but has high production costs and poor stability at high humidity.

2. Molding: A moistened powder blend is compressed in a mold and then dried.
  Molded tablets are more porous than compressed tablets, allowing faster
  disintegration.

3. Sublimation: Volatile ingredients (e.g., camphor, menthol) are added to the
  tablet formulation and later removed by sublimation, leaving a porous matrix
  that rapidly disintegrates.

4. Direct Compression: The simplest and most cost-effective method.
  Superdisintegrants and water-soluble excipients are directly compressed into
  tablets using conventional tableting equipment, preferred for industrial
  scale-up.

5. Spray-Drying: Spray-dried porous powders are compressed into tablets that
  rapidly disintegrate due to their porous structure.

6. Sintering: Thermal treatment to bond particles at temperatures below their
  melting point, creating a porous matrix.

== 3.4 Disintegration Results

The FDA defines ODTs as tablets that disintegrate in less than 30 seconds, while
the European Pharmacopoeia specifies a limit of less than 3 minutes. The
disintegration time is influenced by:

- Porosity: Higher porosity leads to faster water penetration. Most ODT
  technologies aim to maximize porosity.
- Superdisintegrant type and concentration: Crospovidone provides the fastest
  disintegration due to its high capillary activity and low gelling tendency.
- Compression force: Lower compression force increases porosity but reduces
  tablet strength. An optimal balance must be found.
- Binder level: Excessive binder slows water penetration and delays
  disintegration.

Clinical studies reviewed by Fu et al. show that ODTs with optimized
formulations achieve disintegration times of 5 to 30 seconds, providing rapid
drug release, improved patient compliance, and the potential for enhanced
bioavailability through pre-gastric absorption.

= 4 Orodispersible Films (ODFs)

This section summarizes the review by Salawi (2022).

== 4.1 Background

Orodispersible films (ODFs) are thin, flexible polymeric films that disintegrate
or dissolve rapidly in the oral cavity upon contact with saliva. They offer
advantages over ODTs, including faster disintegration (typically 5 to 30
seconds), no risk of choking, ease of handling and storage, and flexible
packaging. The European Pharmacopoeia (Ph. Eur. 9th edition) defines ODFs as
formulations intended for oral administration via the oral cavity, consisting
primarily of a film-forming polymer as the drug carrier.

== 4.2 Formulation Analysis

Salawi (2022) details the key components of ODF formulations:

- Film-forming polymer (40 to 50% w/w): The most critical component. Common
  polymers include HPMC (hypromellose), pullulan, PVA (polyvinyl alcohol),
  sodium CMC, chitosan, gelatin, and maltodextrin. HPMC is the most widely used
  due to its excellent film-forming properties, acceptable taste, and fast
  disintegration.

- Plasticizer (0 to 20% w/w): Glycerin, propylene glycol, PEG, triacetin, or
  castor oil. Plasticizers improve film flexibility and reduce brittleness.

- Drug (1 to 30% w/w): Suitable for drugs with low to moderate doses. Both
  thermostable and thermolabile drugs can be incorporated.

- Other excipients: Sweetening agents (3 to 6%, e.g., sucralose, aspartame),
  saliva stimulating agents (2 to 6%, e.g., citric acid, malic acid), flavoring
  agents, surfactants, and coloring agents.

The key challenge in ODF formulation is balancing disintegration time against
mechanical properties films must be strong enough to withstand handling yet
disintegrate rapidly in the mouth.

== 4.3 Manufacturing Procedures

Salawi (2022) describes several manufacturing techniques:

1. Solvent Casting (most common): The drug and excipients are dissolved or
  dispersed in a volatile solvent. The solution is cast onto a flat surface,
  dried to remove the solvent, and cut into films of desired size. This method
  is suitable for both thermostable and thermolabile drugs, provides uniform
  thickness and drug content, and is the most scalable technique.

2. Hot-Melt Extrusion (HME): The drug and carrier are mixed in solid form,
  heated to melt the carrier (typically around 80 degree C), and extruded
  through a die, followed by calendering into a film. HME is solvent-free and
  suitable for thermostable drugs.

3. Electrospinning: An electric field is used to draw polymer solutions into
  nanofibers, forming a non-woven film matrix. Suitable for thermosensitive
  drugs but has limited scalability.

4. Semisolid Casting: A gel-like mass is cast onto a heat-controlled drum and
  dried into a film. Used for acid-insoluble polymers.

5. 3D Printing: An emerging technology enabling personalized dosing and complex
  film architectures.

== 4.4 Disintegration Results

Salawi (2022) reports that:

- The target disintegration time for ODFs is 5 to 30 seconds, with the Ph. Eur.
  limit being less than or equal to 90 seconds.
- Disintegration time is primarily determined by the polymer type, polymer
  concentration, film thickness, and plasticizer content.
- Solvent-cast HPMC films typically disintegrate within 10 to 40 seconds.
- Pullulan-based films disintegrate faster than HPMC films due to their higher
  water solubility.
- Several disintegration testing methods exist: the petri dish method, slide
  frame method, SFaB (modified) method, and the PharmaTest apparatus. The slide
  frame and SFaB methods are recommended for R&D, while PharmaTest is suitable
  for quality control.
- Thinner films and the incorporation of superdisintegrants (e.g., sodium starch
  glycolate, croscarmellose sodium) further reduce disintegration time.

= 5 Conclusion

Three novel oral solid dosage forms dripping pills (solid dispersion-based),
orally disintegrating tablets, and orodispersible films each offer distinct
advantages in addressing the limitations of conventional dosage forms:

- Dripping pills enhance the dissolution and bioavailability of poorly
  water-soluble drugs through solid dispersion in hydrophilic carriers, and they
  can achieve sustained release when hydrophobic carriers are employed. The
  lycopene dripping pill (Chang et al., 2016) exemplifies a 6-fold improvement
  in oral bioavailability, while traditional pill formulations reviewed by Zuo
  et al. (2021) demonstrate that hydrophobic bases enable sustained release
  profiles.

- Orally disintegrating tablets address dysphagia and improve patient compliance
  through rapid disintegration in the oral cavity. Multiple manufacturing
  technologies (lyophilization, direct compression, molding, sublimation) are
  available, with disintegration times ranging from a few seconds to 3 minutes
  depending on the method and formulation.

- Orodispersible films offer the fastest disintegration (5 to 30 seconds) with
  the added benefits of flexibility, portability, and ease of administration
  without water or risk of choking. Solvent casting remains the most widely used
  manufacturing technique, with HPMC and pullulan as the preferred film-forming
  polymers.

